<p>However, stars and nebulae =E2=80=93 not to mention distant galaxies =E2=
=80=93 are vastly farther than one light-year away. And, if we try to expre=
ss a star=E2=80=99s distance in miles or kilometers, we soon end up with im=
possibly huge numbers. Yet miles and kilometers are what most of us use to =
comprehend the distance from one place on Earth to another. In the late 20t=
h century astronomer Robert Burnham, Jr. =E2=80=93 author of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.amazon.com/Burnhams-Celestial-Handbook-Observers-Universe/dp/04862=
3567X" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">Burnham=E2=80=99s Celestial Handb=
ook</a> =E2=80=93 devised an ingenious way to portray the distance of light=
-years in terms of miles and kilometers. </p>
<p>Keep reading, for a way to comprehend the vastness of the universe, usin=
g units of distance we know and use every day.</p>
<h3>Let=E2=80=99s start with astronomical units</h3>
<p>Burnham started by relating the light-year to the <a href=3D"https://ear=
thsky.org/space/what-is-the-astronomical-unit" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noo=
pener">astronomical unit</a> =E2=80=93 the Earth-sun distance.</p>
<p>One astronomical unit, or AU, equals about 93 million miles (150 million=
 km). </p>
<p>Also, another way of looking at it is this: the astronomical unit is a b=
it more than 8 light-minutes in distance.</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_244077" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-244=
077" style=3D"width: 800px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://earthsky.org/upl/2015/11/light-beam-earth-sun-moon-km-wiki-e1468081677=
540.jpg"><img decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://earthsky.org/upl/2015/11/li=
ght-beam-earth-sun-moon-km-wiki-e1468081677540.jpg" alt=3D"Diagram of sun, =
Earth and moon, labeled. There is a line between the sun and Earth labeled =
150,000,000 km. The moon is to the right side of Earth." width=3D"800" heig=
ht=3D"453" class=3D"size-full wp-image-244077"></a><figcaption id=3D"captio=
n-attachment-244077" class=3D"wp-caption-text">A light beam takes 8 minutes=
 to travel the 93 million miles (150 million km) from the sun to the Earth.=
 Image via Brews Ohare/ <a href=3D"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:=
Sun_to_Earth.JPG" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">Wikimedia Commons</a>.=
</figcaption></figure>
<h3>A light-year, pictured as a mile</h3>
<p>Robert Burnham noticed that, quite by coincidence, the number of astrono=
mical units in one light-year and the number of inches in one mile are virt=
ually the same. </p>
<p>Generally speaking, there are 63,000 astronomical units in one light-yea=
r, and 63,360 inches (160,000 cm) in one mile (1.6 km). </p>
<p>This wonderful coincidence enables us to bring the light-year down to Ea=
rth. So, if we scale the <em>astronomical unit</em> =E2=80=93 the Earth-sun=
 distance =E2=80=93 at one inch, then the light-year on this scale represen=
ts one mile (1.6 km).</p>
<p>The closest star to Earth, other than the sun, is <a href=3D"https://ear=
thsky.org/tonightpost/brightest-stars/alpha-centauri-is-the-nearest-bright-=
star" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">Alpha Centauri</a> at some 4.4 lig=
ht-years away. So, scaling the Earth-sun distance at one inch places this s=
tar at 4.4 miles (7 km) distant.</p>
<p>See?</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_358279" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-358=
279" style=3D"width: 800px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding=
=3D"async" src=3D"https://earthsky.org/upl/2021/04/Alpha_Beta_and_Proxima_C=
entauri_1.jpg" alt=3D"Extremely dense star field with 2 bright stars and a =
small red circle at bottom left." width=3D"800" height=3D"536" class=3D"siz=
e-full wp-image-358279"><figcaption id=3D"caption-attachment-358279" class=
=3D"wp-caption-text">The very faint Proxima Centauri, which is gravitationa=
lly bound to Alpha Centauri, is indicated by a red circle in this image. Pr=
oxima Centauri, is our sun=E2=80=99s nearest neighbor among the stars. A be=
am of light from this star takes about 4 years to travel to Earth. The two =
bright stars are Alpha Centauri and Beta Centauri. Image via Skatebiker / <=
a href=3D"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Alpha,_Beta_and_Proxima_C=
entauri_(1).jpg" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">Wikimedia Commons</a> (=
<a href=3D"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/deed.en" rel=3D"n=
oopener" target=3D"_blank">CC BY-SA 3.0</a>).</figcaption></figure>
<h3>Familiar space objects, conceptualized</h3>
<p>Scaling the astronomical unit at one inch (2.5 cm), here are distances t=
o various bright stars, star clusters and galaxies:</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://earthsky.org/tonightpost/brightest-stars/alpha-centau=
ri-is-the-nearest-bright-star" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">Alpha Cen=
