lowfullscreen=3D""></iframe></p>
<h3>The fastest-moving stuff in the universe</h3>
<p>As mentioned above, light travels at an incredible 186,000 miles per sec=
ond (300,000 km/sec). That=E2=80=99s very fast, indeed. In fact, if you cou=
ld travel at the speed of light, you would be able to circle the Earth=E2=
=80=99s equator about 7.5 times in just one second!</p>
<p>In other words, a light-second is the distance light travels in one seco=
nd, or 7.5 times the distance around Earth=E2=80=99s equator. So, a light-y=
ear is the distance light travels in one year.</p>
<p>How far is that? Multiply the number of seconds in one year by the numbe=
r of miles or kilometers that light travels in one second, and there you ha=
ve it: one light-year. It=E2=80=99s about 5.9 trillion miles (9.5 trillion =
km).</p>
